 Its reasons are as follows: My stated preferences emphasize tightly sequenced, concise collections of hook‑driven singles with memorable melodies, rich vocal harmonies, clear/revealing production and economical arrangements; I also dislike sprawling, double‑disc or overly long compilations, excessive remixes/bonus tracks, murky mastering or mislabelled releases, and sparse documentation.
"10 From 6" aligns much more directly with those preferences. The title itself indicates a short, single‑disc compilation of ten tracks — the sort of concise, deliberately sequenced package I prioritize because it preserves immediacy and repeatability rather than bloating sequencing with dozens of tracks or alternate versions. Its categorization as Classic Rock / AOR also works in my favor: AOR compilations tend to collect tight, hooky singles and foreground vocal arrangements and polished, radio‑ready production rather than overly dense, studio‑heavy layering that obscures melody. A ten‑track AOR compilation is therefore the likelier match for my desire for instant replayability, clear production that highlights vocal detail, and economical arrangements.
By contrast, "Singles 1969-1981" raises several red flags relative to my dislikes. A chronological “Singles” set spanning 12 years is typically much longer and less tightly sequenced — it usually prioritizes completeness over concise flow, which conflicts with my preference for immediacy and tight sequencing. Such multi‑era compilations often present uneven production and mastering from disparate sources (increasing the risk of murky or inconsistent sound), and can be prone to long tracklists, bonus material or variant single versions that bloat the listening experience. Its “Pop; Oldies” designation also suggests a wide stylistic sweep across changing production aesthetics from 1969 to 1981, which can undermine the consistent, clear vocal‑forward presentation I value.
For these reasons I choose "10 From 6" as the better fit for my stated tastes and reject "Singles 1969-1981" as likely too sprawling, potentially inconsistent in mastering and sequencing, and therefore less aligned with my priorities.

